# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ci-train — VPS-mode env file.
#
# Use on the single-node VPS that fronts api.cicyberlab.com.
# The Next.js frontend deploys to Vercel separately — see
# deploy/env/vercel.env.example.
#
# Usage on the VPS:
#   cp deploy/env/vps.env.example deploy/env/vps.env
#   $EDITOR deploy/env/vps.env       # fill in the real password
#   chmod 600 deploy/env/vps.env
#   docker compose --env-file deploy/env/vps.env \
#                  -f deploy/docker-compose.vps.yml \
#                  up -d --build
#
# DO NOT commit deploy/env/vps.env — only this *.example.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ─── Postgres ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
POSTGRES_USER=citrain
# Generate with `openssl rand -base64 32`. Long. Random. Unique.
# This is effectively the database root password.
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=replace-with-long-random-secret
POSTGRES_DB=citrain

# ─── Reverse-proxy trust ──────────────────────────────────────
# Caddy is the one hop in front. Setting this to "0" makes the login
# throttler key on Caddy's loopback IP (all logins share a bucket).
# Setting it to "true" (all hops) lets any client spoof
# X-Forwarded-For and rotate identity per request. "1" is the right
# answer for Caddy or nginx with the headers documented in
# deploy/Caddyfile.example.
TRUST_PROXY=1

# ─── BFF → API forwarded-IP channel ───────────────────────────
# REQUIRED on this VPS api AND in the Vercel project env for the
# web app. The web BFF stamps X-CI-Train-Client-IP and
# X-CI-Train-BFF-Secret on outbound API calls so the API rate-
# limits browser-driven traffic by the real client IP instead of
# the BFF's egress IP. Without this secret all browser logins
# share one throttle bucket regardless of who they came from.
#
# Generate a fresh value (≥16 unguessable random bytes) and set
# the SAME string in both places:
#   openssl rand -hex 32
#
# Trust boundary is the secret itself, not the network path. In
# the Vercel + VPS topology the BFF reaches the api over the same
# public api.cicyberlab.com vhost as any other internet client,
# so deploy/Caddyfile.example deliberately PASSES X-CI-Train-*
# through. Direct public callers can send those headers too, but
# without the matching secret the api guard rejects the override
# and falls back to req.ip — no failure mode raises the rate
# limit. Only add a Caddy `request_header -X-CI-Train-*` strip if
# the deployment has a separate trusted internal BFF-to-API path
# (e.g. WireGuard or a sidecar BFF on the VPS).
BFF_FORWARD_SECRET=change_me_to_a_fresh_openssl_rand_hex_32_value

# ─── Host paths ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Where Postgres data, artifacts, and backups live on the VPS.
# Bind-mounted into the containers by docker-compose.vps.yml.
CITRAIN_DATA_ROOT=/var/lib/citrain

# ─── Seed accounts ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Bootstrap admin + regular-user accounts. M15: passwords are
# env-driven. STRONGLY recommended for the VPS: set both passwords
# explicitly so you have a known credential to log in with after
# a fresh deploy. Without them the seed generates random passwords
# and prints them once into the container log, which is fragile
# (lost after a rotation, hard to share securely).
#
# Generate fresh values (≥10 chars, ideally 24+):
#   openssl rand -base64 24
#
# Re-running the seed is idempotent:
#   - SEED_*_PASSWORD set → password is rotated to that value.
#   - SEED_*_PASSWORD unset and account already exists → the
#     existing password is NOT touched (so a password you changed
#     through the UI or the reset-password CLI sticks).
#
# These are NOT the same as POSTGRES_PASSWORD or BFF_FORWARD_SECRET.
# Those guard infrastructure (database, rate-limit channel); the
# values below are the actual web-login credentials a human types.
#
# Recovery (forgot the admin password):
#   docker compose exec api node dist/scripts/reset-password.js \
#     --email admin@cicyberlab.com --password 'NewPasswordHere'
#
# Role model: `user` accounts solve challenges and view their own
# progress; `admin` accounts can do all of that AND manage other
# users, author/import challenges, and reset passwords. Admins
# are still challenge users.
#
# SEED_ADMIN_EMAIL and SEED_USER_EMAIL MUST be different addresses
# (compared case-insensitively, since the email column is citext).
# If both resolve to the same row the seed exits before any DB
# writes — re-using one mailbox would let the second upsert demote
# the row from admin to user and leave the deploy without an
# enabled admin. Use a plus-alias (Gmail / Fastmail / most
# Exchange tenants) if you only have one inbox:
#   SEED_ADMIN_EMAIL=james@cicyberlab.com
#   SEED_USER_EMAIL=james+user@cicyberlab.com
SEED_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@cicyberlab.com
SEED_USER_EMAIL=user@cicyberlab.com
SEED_ADMIN_PASSWORD=change_me_to_an_openssl_rand_base64_24_value
SEED_USER_PASSWORD=change_me_to_a_different_openssl_rand_value

# Backwards-compat aliases (pre-M15 env-file). Still honored only
# so already-deployed env files keep working — prefer the new
# names above for fresh deploys. Safe to delete in a freshly-
# edited env file.
# SEED_INSTRUCTOR_EMAIL=admin@cicyberlab.com
# SEED_TRAINEE_EMAIL=user@cicyberlab.com
